sql:
SELECT grade_id, COUNT(composition_id) AS composition_count 
FROM compositions
GROUP BY grade_id;

external_knowledge:
- "Improvement" in composition length is defined as the current average composition length being greater than the previous average composition length;
- "More feedback" is defined as the current number of compositions that received feedback being greater than the previous number of compositions that received feedback;
- "Previous submissions" refer to the submissions before the current one in the sequence of the student's submissions.

- "More than one composition" implies the student has submitted at least two compositions;
- "Average revision count" is calculated by summing the revision counts of all compositions and dividing by the number of compositions;
- "Average length of compositions" is calculated by summing the lengths of all compositions in bars and dividing by the number of compositions.

- 'Instructor feedback' can be 'No feedback' if no specific feedback is provided;
- 'Average revision count' is calculated per grade level;
- The results are ordered first by grade level and then by student name.

- "blossomed like flowers" refers to students who have shown significant growth and development in their musical compositions;
- "crafting more than one composition" means the students have created more than one musical piece;
- "refining their work through more than two revisions" means the students have made more than two edits or improvements to their compositions;
- "pieces with an average length that surpasses the threshold of 5 bars" means the compositions are, on average, longer than 5 bars;
- "arrange these prodigies by the richness of their portfolio" means the results are sorted by the total number of compositions in descending order.

- 'budding authors' refers to students who have created compositions;
- 'mentors' refers to instructors assigned to the students;
- 'garden of Grade 2' refers to the grade level where the compositions are created;
- 'more than one story has bloomed' means that the student has created more than one composition.
